# Set up a function to tell me about outliers
# Doing it in a function rather than independently so I can all or not.

def detect_outlier(data_1):
    outliers=[]
    
    Q1=data_1.quantile(q=0.25)
    Q3=data_1.quantile(q=0.75)

    IRQ = Q3-Q1
    
    LQ=Q1-1.5*(Q3-Q1)
    UQ=Q3+1.5*(Q3-Q1)

    for y in data_1:
        if y < LQ or y > UQ:
            outliers.append(y)
            
    return outliers

Maybe add a new Column - cement ratio¶

!! Going to create a new column based on the percentage of cement vs other additives. The idea is that assuming the strength tests were done on a pure cube then a 1 meter ^3 of pure cement vs 1 meter^3 of cement mixed with ash and slag and agg, etc. should have a different strength.

I think this is oversimplifying as one item may be in total opposite of another item or vice versa but I didn’t see a lot of evidence of that from the pair plot. Anyway – just going to throw this together and see what I can see using formula Cement / (Cement + slag + ash + superplastic + coarseagg + fineagg). Going to avoid water as that should disappear when it dries out and age as it is not an additive.

# Set outliers to median
# Doing it in a function rather than independently so I can all or not.

def outlier_to_medium(data, colName):
    Q1 = data[colName].quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = data[colName].quantile(0.75)
    low=Q1-1.5*(Q3-Q1)
#    print(Q1)
#    print(Low)
    high=Q3+1.5*(Q3-Q1)
#    if data[colName] < Low:
#        print(data.colName)
    data.loc[(data[colName] < low) | (data[colName] > high), colName] = data[colName].median()          
    return data

In [91]:
# Create a funciton to evaluate our models.
# This appears to give a differnt score than the ones we got in tthe intial passes but that os OK as long as consitent and 
# I do the base model initially so all is on the same page.
# Recieve most of the ideas for this fucntion from web absed research, can't recall the exact site.
def evaluate(model, test_features, test_labels):
    predictions = model.predict(test_features)
    errors = abs(predictions - test_labels)
    mape = 100 * np.mean(errors / test_labels)
    accuracy = 100 - mape
    print('Model Performance')
    print('Average Error: {:0.4f} degrees.'.format(np.mean(errors)))
    print('Accuracy = {:0.2f}%.'.format(accuracy))
    
    return accuracy

# Create the parameter grid based on the results of random search 
# This looks liek it is going to take a very long time but want ot comapre apples to apples.

## ********************************* NOTE **************************
# Ran this and estimated it was going to take greater than three hours to complete 12,000+ iterations. 
# SIcne my computer times out before this three+ hour period, it was effectively never going to complete
# without excessive manual intervention
#
# Therefore, while I do not think it is fair and now I am comparing apples to oranges, I have limited the param grid slightly 
# purely due to technical reasons.
#
# Decided to limit the max_depth to four vs ten and boostrap only to False to match the best params from the random set.



n_estimators = [int(x) for x in np.linspace(start = 1, stop = 2000, num = 10)]
max_features = ['auto', 'sqrt']
#max_depth = [int(x) for x in np.linspace(4, 110, num = 11)]
max_depth = [4, 10, 30, 100]
max_depth.append(None)
min_samples_split = [2, 5, 10]
min_samples_leaf = [1, 2, 4]
#bootstrap = [True, False]
bootstrap = [False]

               'max_features': max_features,

               'min_samples_split': min_samples_split,

               'bootstrap': bootstrap}

Conclusions and Observations¶

Best Model Observations

  1. For my project the best model was a hyper tuned Gradient Boosting using the Randomized Search
  2. It evaluated out with 96+ % accuracy. One run was 96.209584
  3. This is a little surprising as I expected random forest to be the best performing model. However It does make sense Gradient Boosting was better
  4. The hyper-parameterization gave me a 14.14% percent increase over my base random forest
  5. There were other models that had a better improvement but not enough to overcome the initial accuarcy.

Hyper Parameter coding observations

  1. I don’t think I am doing the hyper parameters quite right. I would think with same parameters going in, then the grid search should at ;east have been equal to randomized search
  2. Grid search takes MUCH longer and for one model, I had to dampen down the params as there is no effective way my hardware could complete the model
  3. I do not understand the models themselves to know which parameters are good candidates for the parameter grid.
  4. If I am not mistaken, I think I am supposed to spit the data into a train, verification and test set. For my project, I only used train and test.
  5. I do not think it matters in this case. I did not go back and tweak parameters so there was not data leak

Other coding observations

  1. Outliers – I changed most o9f the outliers into the median. I was considering capping a few but the more I looked at it, I decided not to.
  2. Age outliers – When removing the outliers it just uncovered more outliers and this went on. Originally I was going to replace the outliers with median twice but this seemed to make it worse.
  3. Scaling – not sure I scaled this correctly. Research said that standard scaling should be used with the distributions are normal. I do not think that the other scaling methods I looked at appeared more appropriate but I am not sure.
  4. My added variable – the percentage of cement compared to additives did not seem to do much. While it showed a decent correlation to strength, the decision tree showed it had almost no importance.
